    <char style="w" strong="H0310">After</char> these <char style="w" strong="H1697">things</char> did <char style="w" strong="H4428">king</char> <char style="w" strong="H0325">Ahasuerus</char> <char style="w" strong="H1431">promote</char> <char style="w" strong="H2001">Haman</char> the <char style="w" strong="H1121">son</char> of <char style="w" strong="H4099">Hammedatha</char> the <char style="w" strong="H0091">Agagite</char>, and <char style="w" strong="H5375">advanced</char> him, and <char style="w" strong="H7760">set</char> his <char style="w" strong="H3678">seat</char> above all the <char style="w" strong="H8269">princes</char> that <char style="add">were</char> with him. <verse eid="EST 3:1" /><verse number="2" style="v" sid="EST 3:2" />And all the <char style="w" strong="H4428">king’s</char> <char style="w" strong="H5650">servants</char>, that <char style="add">were</char> in the <char style="w" strong="H4428">king’s</char> <char style="w" strong="H8179">gate</char>, <char style="w" strong="H3766">bowed</char>, and <char style="w" strong="H7812">reverenced</char> <char style="w" strong="H2001">Haman</char>: for the <char style="w" strong="H4428">king</char> had so <char style="w" strong="H6680">commanded</char> concerning him. But <char style="w" strong="H4782">Mordecai</char> <char style="w" strong="H3766">bowed</char> not, nor did <char style="add">him</char> <char style="w" strong="H7812">reverence</char>. <verse eid="EST 3:2" /><verse number="3" style="v" sid="EST 3:3" />Then the <char style="w" strong="H4428">king’s</char> <char style="w" strong="H5650">servants</char>, which <char style="add">were</char> in the <char style="w" strong="H4428">king’s</char> <char style="w" strong="H8179">gate</char>, <char style="w" strong="H0559">said</char> unto <char style="w" strong="H4782">Mordecai</char>, Why <char style="w" strong="H5674">transgressest</char> thou the <char style="w" strong="H4428">king’s</char> <char style="w" strong="H4687">commandment</char>? <